public support, its refusal of endorsement may conversely send a strong signal to domestic audiences that the action will be exceedingly costly or overly aggressive. With a cogent theoretical and empirical argument, Terrence L. Chapman provides new evidence for how multilateral organizations matter in security affairs as well as a new way of thinking about the design and function of these institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aInternational agenciesxInfluence. 0aInternational agencies. 0aInternational relations. 0aMilitary policyxPublic opinion. 0aSecurity, International. 0aWar, Declaration ofxDecision making. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  apolitics, domestic, war, government, governing, national, warfare, state, military, soldiers, political response, international community, security organizations, un, united nations, foreign policy, public opinion, enforcement power, declaration, decision making, member states, bias, coalition, usa, american, information transmission, authorization.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226101255423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226101255/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles